{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490968"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:25:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:25:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"788"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/788"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.05,0.06,0.13,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104388"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/788"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86718"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44725"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104388"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to your rural Emergency Department with a one-hour episode of constant right-sided abdominal pain. He has a medical history of a bowel resection for a T1 N0 M0 adenocarcinoma five years earlier, and reports being otherwise well, although as a farmer he rarely sees his local doctor. He does not take any regular medications. He smokes 20 cigarettes daily and drinks about four glasses of wine daily . On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals no tenderness, masses, or organomegaly. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatocellular carcinoma","Haemangioma","Pericholecystic abscess","Hepatic metastases","Hydatid disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a well-defined cystic lesion in segment VI of the liver with multiple daughter cysts visible within the main cyst and calcification along the rim. These radiological findings are characteristic of hydatid disease and are likely unrelated to the patient\u0027s current symptoms, which may represent biliary colic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid disease\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by the larval stage of \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/em\u003E, a tapeworm that primarily infects dogs. Humans become intermediate hosts through ingestion of eggs from contaminated food, water, or direct contact with dogs. The patient\u0027s occupation as a farmer is a significant risk factor, as the parasite\u0027s lifecycle involves sheep as intermediate hosts and dogs as definitive hosts. Hydatid cysts typically grow slowly and may remain asymptomatic for years until they become large enough to cause mass effect or rupture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemangiomas\u003C/strong\u003E are benign vascular tumours that typically appear as well-defined, homogeneous lesions with peripheral nodular enhancement on contrast-enhanced imaging. They lack the characteristic daughter cysts and calcified walls seen in this case. Haemangiomas are the most common benign liver tumours but do not match the imaging findings presented.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericholecystic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E would present with persistent pain, fever, and localised tenderness. The imaging would show an ill-defined fluid collection adjacent to the gallbladder with surrounding inflammatory changes. The patient\u0027s brief pain episode and normal examination findings make this diagnosis unlikely, and the imaging does not support it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic metastases\u003C/strong\u003E from colorectal cancer typically appear as multiple hypodense lesions with irregular margins. While this patient has a history of bowel cancer, it was an early-stage tumour (T1 N0 M0) treated five years ago, making metastatic disease less likely. Additionally, metastases would not show the characteristic daughter cysts seen in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a heterogeneous mass with arterial enhancement and venous washout on contrast-enhanced imaging. It usually develops in the setting of chronic liver disease, particularly cirrhosis. While the patient has risk factors (alcohol consumption), the imaging findings of a well-defined cystic lesion with daughter cysts are inconsistent with hepatocellular carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydatid disease is characterised by cystic lesions with daughter cysts and calcified walls on imaging.","Occupational history is crucial when considering zoonotic infections like hydatid disease, particularly in farmers and those working with dogs and livestock.","Incidental findings of hydatid cysts are common, as many patients remain asymptomatic until cysts become large or rupture."],"references":["Marrero JA, Ahn J, Rajender Reddy K; Americal College of Gastroenterology. ACG clinical guideline: the diagnosis and management of focal liver lesions. Am J Gastroenterol. 2014;109(9):1328-47. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25135008/","Keong B, Wilkie B, Sutherland T, et al. Hepatic cystic echinococcosis in Australia: an update on diagnosis and management. ANZ J Surg 2018; 88:26\u201331. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29024292/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86718"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"788"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14420"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14420"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a7a323f5-5702-411b-838c-10a5987e0522.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a7a323f5-5702-411b-838c-10a5987e0522.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":617,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86718"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-01T18:51:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-01T18:51:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"788"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104388"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":